analytic.title: A novel HfNbTaTiV high-entropy alloy of superior mechanical properties designed on the principle of maximum lattice distortion

div.head: Introduction
div.p: In the pursuit for higher strengths for metallic materials, a recent advance is the invention of the concept of high-entropy alloys (HEAs) [1,2], which is a strategy of using a J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f high number of principal elements to form a single phase solid solution. The fundamental principle for the strength of HEAs is solid solution strengthening, achieved by maximum ubiquitous local lattice distortions caused by having every individual atom to neighbor with different atoms in the lattice [3].

Since the invention of this novel concept in 2004, a vast number (over 2000) of HEAs have been created and reported. One subset of these HEAs is the body-centered-cubic (BCC) HEAs. Most BCC transition metal elements used for BCC HEAs have high melting temperatures, thus they are also often known as refractory HEAs (RHEAs). BCC HEAs generally have higher yield strengths compared to the face-centered-cubic (FCC) structured HEAs and the hexagonal-close-packed (HCP) structured HEAs [4,5], because of several concurrent contributions, including the fewer effective slip systems than in the FCC structure and the higher Peierls-Nabarro stresses for moving dislocations than those in FCC and HCP structures [6]. In addition, the common elements forming BCC HEAs appear to differ more in atomic size and cause more severe lattice distortions than those in FCC and HCP HEAs [7].
At the same time, BCC HEAs are also generally more brittle and have poorer malleability [8][9][10].

Different approaches have been trialed to improve the ductility of BCC HEAs [8,[11][12][13]. Transformation-induced plasticity (TRIP) has proven to be effective in reducing the brittleness of BCC HEAs. In these alloys stress-induced BCCHCP transformations may be introduced by lowering the content of some BCC phase stabilizing elements, such as Nb and Ta, and increasing those of HCP phase stabilizing elements, such as Ti, Zr and Hf [14,15]. Such transformations absorb local deformation owing to their crystallographic lattice distortion, thus to relax local stress concentrations within the lattice. This helps to suppress or mitigate early cracking and improve ductility. However, this approach usually upsets the equimolar composition of the HEAs and causes lowering of the yield strength by weakening J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f the solid solution strengthening effect. In addition, the occurrence of a stress-induced transformation prior to dislocation plastic deformation also explicitly implies that the stress required for the transformation is lower than the critical stress required for dislocation plasticity. In this regard, the lowering of the apparent yield strength is intrinsic to this approach. For example, a stress-induced BCCHCP transformation was introduced to a TaHfZrTi alloy by lowering the Ta content to Ta 0.4 HfZrTi. As a result, the fracture strain (ductility) of Ta 0.4 HfZrTi increased from ~2.5% to ~27% but the yield strength decreased significantly from ~1.5 GPa (for yielding by dislocation plasticity) to ~0.4 GPa (for yielding by stress-induced transformation) [16].

Another approach is to design HEAs based on the principle of intrinsic characteristics of constituent elements. First-principles calculations [17] indicate that group V (V, Nb, Ta) elements in the Periodic Table are intrinsically ductile. Crystals of these metals mechanically fail by shear via dislocation movement. In contrast, group VI (Cr, Mo, W) elements are intrinsically brittle and they fail predominantly by cleavage fracture. In addition, an empirical criterion based on the valence electron concentration (VEC) is also proposed for ductility of BCC alloys, i.e., an alloy is ductile when VEC ≤ 4.6 [18]. Using this approach, many HEAs have been designed, with a single phase Hf 0.5 Nb 0.5 Ta 0.5 Ti 1.5 Zr HEA appearing to offer the best properties [18]. This alloy exhibited a large tensile ductility of ~18.8% and a yield strength of 900 MPa. In comparison, some Mo and W containing BCC HEAs, which have higher VECs in the range of 4.6-5.5, show high yield strengths over ~1.2 GPa but limited compressive ductility of below ~9% [10,19,20].

One further independent principle we can apply to further optimize the alloy design for higher strength and higher ductility is to increase the lattice friction for dislocation movement. Lattice friction describes the collective difficulty to move dislocations within a matrix, as expressed by the Peierls potential [21]. It increases with increasing the magnitude J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f of the lattice distortion of the matrix. In this regard, it is a measure of the effectiveness of solid solution strengthening. For the same quantitative composition, the lattice friction stress, or the Peierls potential landscape, of a matrix increases with increasing the atomic size differences among the constituent elements. Therefore, it is possible to achieve better combinations of strength and ductility by optimizing the contributions of all the three principles, i.e., the intrinsic ductility of elements, the VEC criterion, and maximization of atomic size differences among the constituent elements. This study explored the synergy among these three approaches to design BCC HEAs of concurrent high strength and high ductility.

div.head: Experimental
div.p: An equiatomic HfNbTaTiV alloy and an equiatomic HfNbTaTiZr alloy were designed in this study. Button ingots of the alloys were fabricated from high purity elements (>99.99 %) by means of vacuum arc melting in water-cooled copper crucibles in Ar atmosphere. The crystal structures of the as-cast alloys were analyzed by means of X-ray diffraction (XRD) using Cu-K α radiation. The microstructures of the alloys were examined using an optical microscope and a FEI Quanta 650F scanning electron microscope (SEM). The SEM is equipped with an energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) capability for chemical analysis and an electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) detector for crystallographic analysis. SEM samples were etched using an aqueous solution of HNO 3 :HF:H 2 O=1:3:7 in volume ratio. An aberration-corrected FEI Titan Themis G2-300KV transmission electron microscope (TEM) was used to analyze the microstructure and elemental distributions at the nanoscale.

Atomic probe tomography (APT) analysis was performed using CAMECA LEAP 4000X HR instrument. The needle-shaped specimens used for APT analysis were fabricated using a FEI focused ion beam (FIB) milling instrument. Mechanical testing was conducted in compression using an Instron 8860 instrument and a Gleeble 3350 testing machine, using J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f cylindrical specimens of ϕ3 mm×4.5 mm and ϕ4 mm×6 mm in dimension, respectively. All compression tests were performed under an initial strain rate of 10 -3 /s. For each testing, three new samples were used to assure test reproducibility.

div.head: Alloy design
div.p: To design a BCC HEA, Vienna Ab initio Simulation Package (VASP) was used to select potential elements. It predicts that BCC HEAs can be formed by using Hf, Mo, Nb, Ta, Ti, V, W and Zr. Among them, Hf, Nb, Ta, Ti, V and Zr are intrinsically ductile elements [18]. In this study, two alloys were designed using these elements, including a HfNbTaTiV (hereafter referred to as the V-alloy) equimolar alloy as the target design based on the criteria explained above, and a HfNbTaTiZr (hereafter referred to as the Zr-alloy) equimolar alloy, which is the most studied BCC HEA by many researchers [13,[22][23][24][25][26][27][28][29], as a benchmark alloy for comparison. To achieve simultaneously high strength and high ductility, the HfNbTaTiV alloy was designed in three steps, i.e., (1) to ensure a single-phase solid solution (SPSS) structure by element selection based on thermodynamic principles, (2) to ensure maximum lattice distortion for strong solid solution strengthening effect by maximizing atomic size difference, and (3) to ensure sufficiently low valence electron concentration (VEC) for ductility [18].

The calculations for alloy design were conducted using the CALPHAD (Calculation of Phase Diagrams) method with the TCNI8 thermodynamic database supplied by ThermoCalc™. The thermodynamic parameters concerned are the entropy of mixing (∆𝑆 mix ) and enthalpy of mixing (∆𝐻 mix ) of the system, which can be computed using Eq. ( 1). The level of lattice distortion can be evaluated by an atomic radius difference parameter 𝛿 r of all elements included, which can be computed using Eq. ( 2). The VEC of a solid solution can be computed using Eq. (3) [30,31]. (1)

To ensure a SPSS structure, some thermodynamic criteria based on empirical knowledge have been applied, i.e., -15 ≤ ∆𝐻 mix ≤ 5 kJ/mol, 11 J/(K mol) ≤ ∆𝑆 mix ≤ 19 J/(K mol), and 𝛿 r ≤ 6.6% [32]. In addition, it is also suggested that BCC structure is formed when VEC < 6.87, whereas FCC structure is more stable when VEC > 8, and that the BCC structure is ductile when VEC  4.6 [18]. Moreover, the atomic size difference (𝛿 r ) parameter is 𝛿 r = 5.97 % for the V-alloy, compared to 𝛿 r = 5.20 % for the Zr-alloy. The V-alloy also has a valence electron concentration of VEC = 4.6, which satisfies the empirical criterion of ductility for BCC alloys. Based on these calculations, the V-alloy has the promise to be strong and ductile simultaneously. 3.

div.head: Lattice distortion and solid state strengthening
div.p: As presented above, the as-cast HfNbTaTiV alloy is in single phase and contains no second phase inclusions or precipitates for strengthening. To further identify the dominant strengthening mechanism against yielding, the microstructure of the alloy after deformation was also examined. Fig. 6 shows the X-ray diffraction pattern and a TEM micrograph of the alloy after deformation to 45% compression. It is evident that the alloy remained in single BCC phase without any phased transformation (Fig. 6(a)). TEM examination also confirmed that there was no deformation twins within the structure. Dislocation slip dominates the severe deformation process (Fig. 6(b)). Hence, the superior mechanical performance of the HfNbTaTiV alloy is attributed to the high solid solution strengthening caused by high lattice distortions in its matrix, as per the design strategy. To verify this hypothesis, the lattice distortions in the V-alloy and Zr-alloy were analyzed, as presented in Fig. 7. The V-alloy showed a larger interatomic distance fluctuation of 0.2494±0.0116 nm, comparing to 0.2438±0.0058 nm for the Zr-alloy. The large variation of the interatomic distance reflects severe lattice distortion, which is not surprising given that this alloy contains elements of relatively larger differences in atomic radius (Table 2). Fig. 7(e) and (f) shows HAADF-STEM images of the two alloys at a lower magnification, and the corresponding mappings of the lattice strains along [1 ̅ 21 ̅ ] determined by using Peak Pairs Algorithm (PPA), as shown in Fig. 7(g) and (h). It is evident that the V-alloy had a less homogeneous J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f distribution of lattice stains than the Zr-alloy. It is easy to understand that large lattice distortions impose more friction resistance to dislocation movement [56][57][58].

div.head: Conclusions
div.p: (1) A high-strength, high-ductility HfNbTaTiV RHEA was designed by a synergistic approach based on the principles of intrinsic element ductility, maximum atomic size difference for solid solution strengthening, and the valence electron concentration criterion for ductility.

(2) The HfNbTaTiV alloy exhibited a high compressive yield strength of 1350 MPa and a compressive ductility of > 45%. It also retained a high yield strength of 720 MPa and ductility of > 35% at 700 C. Such a combination of properties is superior to most known BCC HEAs. The alloy had a similar ductility but a strength 50% higher than the HfNbTaTiZr control alloy.
